WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.100
Thank you very much to the DAVA team for inviting me to give this talk.

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:07.740
I'm going to talk about strategies to mitigate ocular toxicity from Belomav.

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:14.660
So Belomav is back, as we've heard, but can we manage the ocular toxicities?

00:00:15.540 --> 00:00:20.620
I would argue that, as we've talked about in the era of bispecifics and CAR-T, Belomav

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:25.060
still retains some relevance as an effective BCMA-targeted therapy for patients who may

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:29.100
not be appropriate for a T-cell redirecting therapy.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:38.200
We've also seen from DREAM7 and DREAM8 that efficacy is still quite significant, with

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:42.100
DREAM7 demonstrating a significant PFS and OS benefit.

00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:47.460
However, the key challenge is, can we manage the ocular toxicity that we see with this

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:47.700
drug?

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:55.700
Ocular toxicity with Belomav is generally reversible and can be managed with dose holds

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:59.160
and interval extension, dosing interval extension.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:01.820
But it's important to note that it is very common.

00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:08.000
In the DREAM7 study, according to the package insert, 92% of patients had ocular toxicity.

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:15.500
So before we go forward, I just want to show what these ocular toxicities actually look

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:16.280
like on exam.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:25.240
So shown here on the left is in vivo confocal microscopy, with the top row being the

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:27.100
pre-treatment exam.

00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:29.680
And then you can see, with the development of...

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:34.540
With the development of these toxicities, you can visualize these superficial punctant

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:38.080
keratopathy, these microcysts that develop in the cornea on the bottom row.

00:01:39.020 --> 00:01:42.060
And then shown on the right is the slit lamp exam findings.

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:54.360
To better define what's actually going on in the cornea, we participated in a multicenter

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:59.520
effort to collect some corneal samples.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:07.760
By either impression cytology or superficial keratectomy in addition to tear fluid collection.

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:16.540
And this study showed that there were corneal epithelial changes characterized by eosinophilic

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:19.400
inclusions and apoptosis in the cornea.

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:24.360
In the ADC, the antibody drug conjugate was detected in the tear fluid in most of these

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:25.360
patients.

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:29.360
And this pattern suggested that the drug enters the cornea via the cornea.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:30.360
And this is a very common pattern in the ADC.

